const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Implant vs. IUD: Choosing a Long-Acting Reversible Contraceptive",
    "description": "A detailed comparison of the Nexplanon implant and intrauterine devices (IUDs), exploring insertion, side effects, and how to choose the right LARC for your body.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "The Nookie Nook"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which is more effective, the implant or the IUD?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Both are extremely effective. The implant (Nexplanon) is technically the most effective reversible method available, with a failure rate of 0.05%. IUDs have a failure rate of 0.2% to 0.8%. Functionally, both provide over 99% protection."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does the implant leave a scar?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, insertion and removal of the implant typically leave a very small scar (a few millimeters wide) on the inner upper arm. For most people, it is barely noticeable once healed."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you feel the implant in your arm?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You cannot feel the implant during normal daily activities, but if you gently press the skin where it was inserted, you should be able to feel the small, flexible rod beneath the surface."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="Implant vs. IUD: Choosing a LARC"
  description="Compare the Nexplanon implant and IUDs side-by-side. Understand the differences in insertion, side effects, and how to choose the right method for you."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/implant-vs-iud"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Implant vs. IUD: Choosing a LARC</h1>
      <p>Comparing the two most effective, "fit and forget" birth control methods.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Long-Acting Reversible Contraceptives (LARCs) are the gold standard of birth control. Because they don't require daily attention, they boast typical use effectiveness rates of over 99%. The two main types of LARCs are the contraceptive implant and Intrauterine Devices (IUDs). Choosing between them often comes down to personal comfort, placement preference, and how your body reacts to specific hormones.</p>

      <h2>The Contraceptive Implant (Nexplanon)</h2>
      <p>The implant is a small, flexible rod—about the size of a matchstick—that a healthcare provider inserts just beneath the skin of your inner upper arm.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>How it Works & Duration</h3>
        <p>It slowly releases a type of progestin (etonogestrel) into your body, which prevents ovulation and thickens cervical mucus. It is FDA-approved for up to 3 years of use, though some studies suggest it may be effective for up to 5 years.</p>

        <h3>The Insertion Process</h3>
        <p>The provider numbs a small area on your arm with a local anesthetic injection. The implant is then pushed under the skin using a specialized applicator. The procedure takes only a few minutes, feels like a slight tugging (if anything), and usually requires a small bandage afterward.</p>

        <h3>Pros and Cons</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pros:</strong> The most effective reversible method available. Highly discreet. Reversible at any time.</li>
          <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Unpredictable bleeding is the most common side effect. Some users experience continuous spotting, while others stop getting their periods entirely. Requires a minor surgical procedure to remove.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>The Intrauterine Device (IUD)</h2>
      <p>An IUD is a small, T-shaped plastic device inserted through the cervix into the uterus. There are hormonal and non-hormonal options.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>How it Works & Duration</h3>
        <p><strong>Hormonal IUDs</strong> (Mirena, Liletta, Kyleena, Skyla) release progestin locally into the uterus, thickening cervical mucus and thinning the uterine lining. They last 3 to 8 years depending on the brand.<br/>
        <strong>Copper IUDs</strong> (Paragard) release copper ions that are toxic to sperm. They last up to 10-12 years.</p>

        <h3>The Insertion Process</h3>
        <p>Insertion involves a pelvic exam. The provider uses a speculum, cleans the cervix, measures the uterus, and then pushes the IUD through the cervix. The process takes a few minutes but can cause a strong pinch or intense cramping.</p>

        <h3>Pros and Cons</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Longest-lasting reversible method. Hormonal options often lighten or eliminate periods. Copper option is entirely hormone-free.</li>
          <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Insertion can be painful. Copper IUDs can cause heavier, crampier periods. Risk of expulsion (the body pushing the device out), though this is rare.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>How to Choose Between Them</h2>
      <p>Consider the following factors when deciding:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Placement:</strong> Would you prefer the device in your arm or your uterus? Some people are uncomfortable with pelvic exams and prefer the arm implant.</li>
        <li><strong>Hormone Preference:</strong> If you want a 100% hormone-free option, the Copper IUD is the only choice. If you want localized hormones, a hormonal IUD is better, as the implant releases hormones systematically.</li>
        <li><strong>Period Control:</strong> If you suffer from heavy, painful periods, a hormonal IUD is often prescribed to lighten them. The implant's effect on periods is much more unpredictable.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Further Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/birth-control-comparison">Back to Birth Control Comparison</a></li>
        <li><a href="/iud-guide-complete">The Complete IUD Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/birth-control-side-effects">Managing Birth Control Side Effects</a></li>
        <li><a href="/birth-control-pill-guide">Alternative: The Birth Control Pill</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
